rComments: Obviously Metcalfe knew her stuff;  but in a job in which its your job to clearly and concisely relay relevant  information, she misses the mark.  Knowing that her lecture technique/capability might be a problem, she could have at least better  organized the class outside of the lectures, which she did not.  I would not repeat this experience.
Expensive texts that we used only once. And the exam questions came from obscurity.

Expensive textbooks, jumbled presentation and loses her voice all the time. Also tries to muddle her way through vast swathes of history interspaced with useless details- for example, 20 minutes on the corrolary to the Paris Peace Treaty of 1763 with maybe 5 minutes from 1763 to 1867.

Although Heather is obviously very passionate and knowledgeable, the method of testing used is befuddling. Her lectures are dense with very detailed information and it is next to impossible to understand how to prioritize material for tests.

The course material comes across as basic and easy, however to make up for this, Metcalfe makes the midterms and exams ridiculously detail-oriented and hard.  Even the TAs lamented about the obscurity of the exam questions.  I would avoid her if you can.
